Explanations on global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report for the year 2001.
In the study covering 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy the top three positions, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe are at the bottom.
(All rankings can be found at www.weforum.com.)
As the co-leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there also economic competition among countries besides military competition?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined very precisely: namely as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth over the medium term – that is, over a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries in the world could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
Nevertheless, it is useful to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Each country is interested in knowing whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep up with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some respects, economic growth is comparable to a sporting competition, in which the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries compete, for example, for internationally mobile capital.
The more a country can secure foreign direct investments, the less another country gets.
This becomes clear when countries compete for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor plant, various countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the contract is fierce, and often countries also offer tax incentives, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to local university study programs.
This year, we measured a country's competitiveness (growth potential) based on three broad criteria: (1) Technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we identified indicators whose average values were calculated using a specific method, in order to create an overall growth and competitiveness index.
The technology criterion refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and adopt technologies developed elsewhere.
Some countries, such as the USA, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden, invest heavily in research and development and therefore achieve high scores in the area of innovation.
Other countries, such as Argentina and Brazil, invest less in research and development and therefore achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovative countries also enjoy high levels of wealth due to these innovations.
In this area, the USA, Canada, and Finland hold the top three positions on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of governance.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts impartial and incorruptible?
Can we trust that the government will fulfill its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and degenerate judges.
High ethical standards promote a country's economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are leading worldwide, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also the top performers in the ranking.
Corruption is virtually unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced government budget, a realistic exchange rate for the national currency, the ability of businesses and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
As seen in Asia in the late 1990s, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can destroy economic growth, even if businesses are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: the innovation-friendly and the non-innovation-friendly.
Only about 20 countries are actively engaged in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, an excellent system of technological innovation is considered a prerequisite for sustained competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, state laboratories should be world-class, and the government and industry should invest heavily in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the percentage of students who, after completing compulsory education, attend higher schools and universities.
In the USA and Canada, this percentage is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is equally important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed domestically within the country.
Some countries specialize in the import of new technologies, while others do not.
Over the past ten or fifteen years, a large portion of technology imports has occurred through foreign direct investments.
American companies that invested heavily in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought new technologies with them, which increased the efficiency of production in the respective economy of the target country.
Therefore, it was entirely sensible for the concerned countries to strive vigorously for these foreign investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one or two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for assessing short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of the major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that occupy the top positions this year, such as the USA or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others, which are ranked further down, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
Partly, the economic slowdown is linked to the September 11 terrorist attacks, but it is also becoming increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the US will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth within the next five years.
